<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> Claire Morgan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (CYS 107)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">I would like to submit the following comments as part of the cycling safety consultation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">1. General information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> &amp; context</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">am a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“utility cyclist” living in the rural village community of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ovingdean</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the eastern outskirts of Brighton in East Sussex. The village is bounded on all sides by main roads including the A259 trunk coastal road to the south.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lthough I am a Brighton &amp;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Hove City Council officer, I am writing in a personal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capacity f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rom the perspective of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a resident of a city which is apparently the UK’s least car-dependent outside London. Yet, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s someone who has placed concern and action for the environment at the core </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of my lifestyle since the early eighties, I have become increasingly concerned about (a) the relentless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">march of a “car culture” and (b) the resulting, highly damaging in every respect, “them and us ‘war’ ” which has developed between regular drivers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and cyclists. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e must do everything we can to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">people to cycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, more often – the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reasons for, and benefits of, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this are well documented.  As a society, we urgently need to pursue a variety of enhanced and new measures, targeted at ALL road </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">users,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will support and enable safe and responsible cycling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. But with th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is encouragement must come a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">corresponding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understanding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that cyclists cannot </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use their relative superiority in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">speed and strength of their mode of transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> compared to pedestrians to intimidate and thus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">non-car-borne </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">road/street users.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is something I have been dismayed to observe increasingly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the city of Brighton and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Hove, and I can only ascribe it to the attitudes mentioned in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2 above.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">2. Roads, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">highway </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">layout</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">, road speeds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">and maintenance</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the widespread existence of dedicated cycle lanes in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bike-friendly countries such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Holland, Belgium, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Denmark</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Germany</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, I d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o NOT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">believe that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">simply b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lanketing this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">segregated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cle lanes is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the answer to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">improv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing cycle safety. Indeed, the above-listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">countries would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not claim it is: their situations ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e the result of an average of 25 years+ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of positive, innovative cycle-promoting action. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As always, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> intimated above, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">range of long-term measures, linked to comprehensive education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> programmes for all road users,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and in some cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">improved and extended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">leg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">islation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, is the best solution.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">orralling cyclists into special lanes militates against </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">normalising cycling as a transport mode and nurtures too many motorists’ belief that cyclists should not be on “their” road when and if there is no alternative route, or a cyclist chooses not to use a provided path.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Segregated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cycle lanes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in my v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iew </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more appropriate for “high-volume” urban areas, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for linking these areas along key arterial or “desire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">routes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">” where there is significant potential for harm to cyclists.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycle paths </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">MUST be continuous, sensibly joined up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, or safety is again compromised as cyclists are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">repeatedly and/or unexpectedly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“turfed out” onto the highway. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cycle lanes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should also be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">maintained on the same maintenance/repair schedule as the highway, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">including cutting back vegetation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This can include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> requiring private homeowners to prune back vegetation emanating from their premises. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Outside urban areas, where there may nevertheless be roads carrying fast traffic (such as in my local area), where pavements exist these should wherever possible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">be re-de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">signated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and signed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">as shared-use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This will improve cyclists’ (and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">drivers’ )</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> safety, as well as encouraging more cyclists.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">olouring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> all cycle lanes, whether kerb-lined or not, in a different colour to give clarity to cyclists and other road users including pedestrians (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> blue cycle lanes in London).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This also raises awareness of cycling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> &amp; cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in general …</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Page 2</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.4. Re-designating an increased number of one-way smaller urban/city centre routes as able to be used as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">two-way for cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It is my observation in Brighton and Hove that cyclists, like water, will always prefer the shortest and quickest route, and wil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l often be prepared to break the law on one-way streets to achieve this, thus compromising other road users’ and their own safety. A similar increase in the number of routes where all traffic except cyclists may turn right, left or go straight ahead would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be helpful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the same reason.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Brighton &amp; Hove has introduced an extensive programme of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">20mph zones</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including many around schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. While not necessarily popular with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">drivers, it has been widely welcomed by cyclists and other road users as supporting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> road safety in general, not simply for cyclists. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that these zones are, in the main, not supported/’enforced’ by road humps, which could impede the comfortable passage of cyclists, buses and emergency vehicles.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Road repair and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> generally should be carried out in a manner which does not leave a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“gutter gap”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where asphalt ceases before the kerb or verge: this creates a hazard for cyclists (and moped/motorbike users) when and if they are pushed towards the side of the ro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ad by traffic, or out of nervousness. Such improved road surfacing would also benefit pedestrians.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Police and traffic wardens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> must be encouraged to clamp down on parking across cycle lanes, and the few cases where parking across cycle lanes is permitt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed should be abolished. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">3. Helmets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and cycle equipment</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> am NOT a supporter of compulsory bike helmet wearing, and in fact believe that legislating to make adult cycl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ists do so is counter-productive, as it militates against the ease and simplicity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of just getting on a bike and riding away</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ata about the benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or otherwise to individual cyclists’ safety from wearing helmets is polarised – at least for adults.  There is evidence showing that drivers see helmet-wearing cyclists as less vulnerable, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thus drive less carefully: there is also evidence indicat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing that cyclists themselves cycle less carefully if they are wearing a helmet, for similar reasons. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Further information, however, indicates that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">helmet wearing for children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">beneficial due to the different way in which children tend to fall from their b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ikes, compared to adults, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> children tend to sustain more head injuries when they fall from a bike than adults, although of course collisions with motorised transport are identically dangerous for all age groups.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Improving road maintenance (see [2] above)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would help reduce the need anyway!</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All new bikes sold should be required to have an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">enhance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d level of reflective items </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on board</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – something as simple as a range of stickers would be helpful.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">4.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Training</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The nationwide children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cycle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">proficiency” scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is not compulsory, but it should be made so, and centrally funded – to include secondary-aged children.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bus and PSV drivers already undergo cycle/cyclist awareness training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – this should be made compulsory, with a requirement t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hat it is refreshed on a regular basis. Brighton &amp; Hove City Council runs a programme whereby cyclists are invited to sit in a bus driver’s cab, to identify the blind spots. I would like to see this programme extended for cyclists.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Page 3</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">. Public info</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">rmation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and awareness-raising</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The big success of making drinking and driving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">socially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unacceptable came through public information campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> over a sustained period of time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as did other successful campaigns like smoking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cessation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The scope for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">helping </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the safety of cycling through such public information campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is immense. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Campaigns don’t need to be as graphic as some countries (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Australia) have chosen to do, but a campaign could take forms such as the following:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alerting people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the need to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> enco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urage cycling, perhaps highlighting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the health benefits of cycling as well as ease of parking and reducing congestion and emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alerting motorists to the danger of opening doors without lookin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Making motorists aw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are of the need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">extra space betwe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en them and cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (see “legislation”, section 6 below)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Encouraging cyclists to be responsible a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd not to terrorise pedestrians</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many motorists view cyclists as freeloaders, claiming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they themselves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pay road tax and fuel duty, while cyclists use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> state-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">funded road infrastructure for ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">free</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (if they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> pay tax, they pay for it indirectly so it’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s not really of course</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> some motorists it feels that way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). Public information film</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s about the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> benefits to society of cycling, including mention of the fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ct that cyclists are expected to maintain their bikes in a roadworthy state (see 6 below) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could defuse some of this anger.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Legislation</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Highway Code</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> needs to be updated, so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is less focused on motorised vehicles, and more inclusive of the safety-enhancing needs of other road users including cyclists. This could include stating a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">minimum space between vehicles and bikes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, both while passing and before and after overtaking. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Consideration of introducing a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“presumption of guilt” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">law, such as operates in other continental European countries, whereby in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the event of a collision between a cyclists and a motorised vehicle, the driver of the latter is automatically assumed to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at fault, unless it can be proved otherwise. This legislative approach appears to cement an attitude of greater respect for cyclists’ safety and well-being from drivers.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Enshrining in law a requirement for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bicycles to be kept in a roadworthy state</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">7.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Cyclists are not necessarily a special case …</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The need to encourage cycling does not mean </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ignoring others’ rights to fairness and respect. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Any message </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public information films or general government guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be that with rights come </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">responsibilities, and c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">yclists should be held accountable for their own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">propriate cycling in the same way as motorists should be.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p></div></body></html>